        <h3>Set up daily reporting workflows</h3>
        <p>Daily reports are your eyes and ears on a job site you're not visiting. Require supers and foremen to submit daily reports every day — even if the report is short. A daily report showing crew counts, work completed, weather, and open issues gives you the information needed to manage a project remotely without surprises.</p>

        <p>Tools that make daily reporting easy (and therefore more consistently done):</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Raken:</strong> Voice-to-text daily reports completed in 5 minutes from the field. Formatted PDF output suitable for sharing with clients and GCs.</li>
          <li><strong>Buildertrend daily log:</strong> Built into the PM platform; works fine for residential projects.</li>
          <li><strong>Procore daily logs:</strong> Well-structured for commercial projects with subcontractor activity tracking.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Establish photo and video documentation standards</h3>
        <p>Photos replace physical walk-throughs when you're managing remotely. Establish clear expectations for what gets photographed — rough-in before walls close, mechanical connections, structural elements, progress milestones, and any issues or damage discovered. Photos should be geotagged and tied to specific projects in your PM platform.</p>

        <p>Video walk-throughs via smartphone (shared via your PM platform or a simple link) can replace many site visits entirely. A 3-minute phone walk-through from a trusted superintendent is often enough to assess progress and spot issues.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Build remote-ready workflows</h2>

        <h3>Standardize your schedule format</h3>
        <p>A well-maintained schedule is the anchor of remote project management. If your schedule is accurate, you can manage most issues without being on site — because you know what should be happening and can cross-reference against daily reports. Update your schedule weekly (at minimum) and share it with all parties through your PM platform.</p>

        <h3>Create clear escalation paths</h3>
        <p>Define which decisions field personnel can make independently vs. which require you. Issues that cause schedule or cost impacts above a threshold (say, any change order over $500) should have a clear escalation protocol. Field staff who know when to escalate — and have a fast way to reach you — prevent small issues from becoming expensive surprises.</p>

        <h3>Handle change orders digitally</h3>
        <p>Change orders managed by phone call and verbal approval are a liability risk and a financial tracking failure waiting to happen. Use your PM platform's change order workflow — or at minimum, email approval — for every scope change. Digital change order approval creates a clear audit trail and prevents disputes at project close.</p>

        <h3>Client communication cadence</h3>
        <p>For residential projects, define how often you'll proactively update the client — weekly status updates at minimum, plus immediate communication for schedule changes or unexpected issues. A client portal (Buildertrend, Houzz Pro) where clients can log in to see photos and schedule updates dramatically reduces "where are we?" phone calls that eat your remote management time.</p>

