        <h2>Step 3: The field team is everything</h2>

        <h3>Your super is your proxy</h3>
        <p>Remote management only works if you have a trusted, capable superintendent or site lead who is physically present and has the judgment to handle day-to-day decisions. No amount of software replaces this person. Invest in finding, developing, and retaining good field leadership — it's the single most important factor in successful remote management.</p>

        <h3>Train your team on documentation standards</h3>
        <p>Software only works if the field team actually uses it. Train your supers and foremen on the specific documentation expectations — how to fill out daily reports, which photos to take and how to tag them, how to log time and materials. Make it easy (mobile apps, voice input) and make it expected (review the data they submit so they know it matters).</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Financial visibility without being on site</h2>

        <h3>Track committed costs, not just invoices</h3>
        <p>By the time a supplier invoice arrives, the spending decision has already been made. Managing a project financially from off-site requires tracking purchase orders, subcontract amounts, and change orders as committed costs — so you can see financial status before bills arrive. Any PM platform worth using tracks committed costs and shows budget vs. actual in real time.</p>

        <h3>Review financial reports at least weekly</h3>
        <p>Off-site managers should review job cost reports weekly: budget vs. actual by cost code, open purchase orders, pending change orders, and projected cost at completion. This frequency catches problems early enough to address them before they compound.</p>

        <h2>Common remote management pitfalls</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Assuming daily reports are accurate:</strong> Spot-check with random video calls or occasional site visits. Don't let remote management become invisible management.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the RFI process:</strong> Verbal clarifications on design questions don't create a paper trail. Remote management makes RFI discipline even more important.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-relying on text messages for decisions:</strong> Important decisions that affect cost or schedule should be documented in your PM platform, not in a text thread that disappears.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting subcontractor coordination:</strong> Sub coordination that happened naturally on-site needs to be actively managed when you're remote. Weekly coordination calls or check-ins with key subs prevent miscommunication.</li>
        </ul>

